-- Rebar Rises for Third Day as Stockpiles Fall for Second Week
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-04-08T04:03:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-08/rebar-rises-for-third-day-as-stockpiles-fall-for-second-week.html
Steel reinforcement-bar futures in
 Shanghai  gained for a third consecutive session as inventories
in  China , the world’s largest user, fell for a second week.  The contract for delivery in October rose as much as 0.8
percent to 3,827 yuan ($617) a metric ton on the Shanghai
Futures Exchange and was at 3,826 yuan at 11:30 a.m. local time.
The bourse was closed April 4-5 for public holidays.  Rebar  inventories  in China declined for a second week to
10.1 million tons as of March 29, compared with 10.2 million
tons two weeks ago, the highest level in at least three years,
according to data from Shanghai Steelhome Information.  “The drop in physical stockpiles brought some positive
sentiment to the market,” Xia Caijun, an analyst at GF Futures
Co., said in a research report today. Price may find technical
support at 3,700 to 3,800  yuan , Xia said.  Spot  iron ore  at Tianjin port was unchanged at $135.90 a
dry ton on April 5, according to The Steel Index Ltd. The
average spot  price  of rebar was unchanged at 3,630 yuan a ton on
April 3, according to Beijing Antaike Information Development Co.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
